summary.seg:
This medical manuscript consists of six independent parts:
Part 1 (pp. [i]-[vi] and pp. [vii]-[x])
Part 2 (pp. 1-172)
Part 3 (pp. 173-210, 213-226, 353-354)
Part 4 (pp. 211-212)
Part 5 (pp. 227-242
Part 6 (pp. 243-352, 355-412) Although the six parts were produced separately in England, they were probably joined together at a relatively early stage. This is suggested by the recurrence of the name and monogram of a sixteenth-century owner (Francis Rolleston) in different parts of the manuscript. Parts 1 and 4 both both have connections with Darley Abbey in Derbyshire, suggesting that the manuscript may have been brought together in whole or in part at this monastery.

Dr Clarck Drieshen
Project Cataloguer
Cambridge University Library

supportDesc.support: Parts 1, 2, 4, 5 and 6 consist of parchment leaves. Part 3 consists of paper leaves. There are parchment tabs on pp. 41-42, 271-272, 333-334 373-374, and 393-394.

foliation.p: Written in ink in the upper right-hand corner of the recto of each leaf.
pp. 169[bis]-170[bis] are part of a parchment strip that has been erroneously paginated with the number '169' on its recto. pp. [192a]-[192b] are part of a paper stub after p. 192.

collation.p: The collation formula for this volume begins with Part 2 (i.e. it excludes the leaves in Part 1 formed from a recycled account roll).

signatures.p: Arabic numerals have been written on the lower right-hand corners of the first rectos of quires by a 19th/20th-century hand.

supportDesc.condition: A strip of parchment, used in order to repair the upper margin of pp. 171-172, and a scrap of parchment found between pp. 170 and 171, are now kept in melinex folders inside the front cover of the manuscript. These have not been photographed.

binding.p: Old 14th or 15th-century binding of skin over wooden boards with the remains of a clasp and pin at the front and rear covers

provenance.p: John Argentine (d. 1507) Argentine, John, d. 1507, royal physician and provost of King's College, Cambridge: possibly belonged to him, as indicated by Italian inscriptions in a hand that apparently resembles his (see Rhodes (1956), p. 212).

Francis Rolleston Rolleston, Francis: perhaps the same Francis Rolleston of Lea Manor, Staffordshire, who was convicted and imprisoned for a plot for the liberation of Queen Mary in 1571. His ownership inscription on p. 1 ('francisco e segnior et patrono ill mio Rollestono') and p. 243 ('Liber F.R.'). His 'F.R.' monogram in the upper margins of pp. 173, 243 (x4: once as part of an ownership inscription, once with the motto: 'in meglio spero', once as an independent monogram, and once written inside a large initial 'O'), 271, 285 (with the motto: 'Ainsi et mieulx poyet estre') and [iv].

One or more members of the Minors family of Lichfield, StaffordshireMinors family of Lichfield, Staffordshire, owned in the (?) first half of the 17th century: the name of 'Richard Minors' inscribed in the upper margin of p. 331; the names of 'Margerry Minors / Thomas Minors / Nicholas Minors / Raphe Minors / Walter Minors / Robert Minors / Richard Minors / William Minors' inscribed in the lower margin of p. 262; 'Thomas' [2x] inscribed in the outer margin of p. 376 'Nicholas Minors' inscribed in the outer margin of p. 404; previously unidentified but their names match with those of the childeren of Richard Minors of Uttoxeter and Margerie Allington, who had sons named Robert, Walter, Richard, William, Raphe, Nicholas, and a daughter named Margerie. Two of the previous had sons named 'Thomas'. Several of them were recorded as alive in 1663 in Collections for a History of Staffordshire Volume 5, Part 2 (1885), p. 214.

William Moore (1590-1659) Moore, William, 1590-1659, BA, MA, fellow of and lecturer in rhetoric at Gonville and Caius College, and librarian of Cambridge University Library (see Pouzet (2017), p. 54).

history.acquisition: Given or bequeathed by William Moore Moore, William, 1590-1659 to Gonville and Caius College in 1659: its armorial bookplate pasted on the inside of the upper cover, inscribed with the classmark numbers '84' and '166'; number 1172 in the catalogue of the College's manuscripts in Edward Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (c. 1697).

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on the description provided by M.R. James James, M.R. (Montague Rhodes), 1862-1936, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, 2 vols (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1908) and Kari Anne Rand SchmidtManuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge (Cambridge: Brewer, 2001).

msItem.title: Fragment of an account roll of the Augustinian monastery of Darley Abbey in Derby, Derbyshire, dated 1444-1445
msItem.rubric: [ii] Compotus domini Rogeri Abbatis superuisoris thesaur. et fratrum Henr. Kelyngworth et Johannis Milton de omnibus expensis
msItem.incipit: [ii] In primis eidem comput. sol. ecclesie omnium sanctorum Derbeye pro ministrellis et al.
msItem.explicit: [vi] Item pro dimidio C. de spikyngis .iij. d - Summa .xxv. s. ij.d.
msItem.finalRubric: [vi] Summa totalis expensis .xxxxj. li. xiij. s. iiij. d
msItem.note: M.R. James identified the origin of this account role as 'a monastery in or near Derby', but Ker (1964), p. 56 securely identified the monastery as Darley Abbey: two of the persons named in the rubric can be positively identified as, respectively, Roger de Newton, abbot of Darley Abbey between 1432-35, and his successor Henry de Killingsworth, who was abbot between 1453 and 1477.

msItem.title: Medical recipes
msItem.note: Six recipes, entitled: A plaster for costyfnes, A powdir for the same, To make a esey laxe, A gud oynement for the palsee, contra frigiditatem in febribus, and contra sciaticam vel dolorem in iuncturis. The collection also contains a (?) charm: Ad missam falces .C. mis. bene fle feodum lex.
The medical recipes on p. [v] are in same hand as scribe who copied recipes onto pp. 224-226 and pp. 353-354.

msItem.title: ? Fragment of an account roll of the Augustinian monastery of Darley Abbey in Derby, Derbyshire, dated 1444-1445
msItem.note: This page contains the offset of a text that was once pasted on a leaf on the inside of the rear cover but is poorly legible due to heavy damage and the fact that the offset text is now displayed in reverse; however the script suggests that it may concern another portion of the account roll of the Augustinian monastery of Darley Abbey in Derby, Derbyshire, of which another fragment survives at pp. [ii]-[vi].

extent.seg: Fragments: pp. [i]-[vi] have been made from two leaves from another manuscript by turning them at a 90 degree angle and folding them vertically; this created a booklet of two bifolio from which the fourth leaf was cut off.

p.seg: Ruled in ink, frame only. Single columns. Text is written below the top line.

handNote.p: The account roll on pp. [ii], [iii], and [vi] is copied copied by a single hand in a cursive script with both Anglicana and Secretary features.
The medical recipes on p. [iv] are copied by a single hand in a in a cursive script with both Anglicana and Secretary features.

decoDesc.p: This part of the manuscript does not contain any significant forms of decoration.

origin.origDate: The account roll refers to Roger de Newton as the abbot, and his abbacy at Darley Abbey lasted from 1432 until 1435; however, it is possible that the account roll is a later copy.

provenance.p: Written in Darley Abbey in Derby, Derbyshire, as the account roll concerns this monastery; also listed as Medica, etc. (partly in English) in MLGB3 [mlgb3.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/mlgb/book/1861/] [accessed 29 June 2023]

msItem.title: Tract on humours and inauspicious days for medical treatement
msItem.incipit: 207 After þe sentens of tholome in his expositour haly propone hunc in þe first quadur of þe mone and þe thryd þe humerus of monnes body and womonnes go forth fro þe induremore partyes vntyll þe vttur partyes and þai are aftur flodes of þe whylke þe natour gro in hem in þoo quadurs is not conuenient to receyue purgacions
msItem.explicit: 208 also he [Campanus] syes he knew a mon þat hade grett payne of fistule in þe hede of his ȝerde and hyt was cutt þe mone beyng in scorpion þe whylk syne has dunacion in þat parte and in þe same howre of cuttyng in þe handis of hem þat held hym he dyed withowte any oþer cause bott onely þat
msItem.note: The tract refers to Ptolemy, Haly and Campanus.

msItem.title: Tract on auspicious times for giving medicine
msItem.incipit: 208 For to knowe what tyme houes to be gyuen a medcyn laxityue or ony oþer whatsomeuer hyt be hyt es to note þat in the body of mane ar fowre naturall vertuse þat es to say attractyue retentyve dygestyue and expulsyue vertu
msItem.explicit: 209 if the mone in the bygynnyng of a sekenes be in a syne menabull þat sekenes es mutabull yf hit be in a syne stabull hyt schall be abydyng yf hit be bytwix both the sekenes schall be meen

msItem.title: Treatise on auspicious and inauspicious days as the basis for diagnosis and giving medicine
msItem.incipit: 209" If any man haue almanak and wyll accede more tyll the trowthe os towchyng the houre of the bygynnyng of the sekenes
msItem.explicit: 210 the mon þan schall be a gude terminacyon and endyng of the sekenesse namely nad þay be nat coniuned bodley or be aspecte os beholdyng with the lorde of the howce of deth the whilk es the 8 for þat part of heuen and hys lord has aspecte to all maner of kynd of deth

msItem.title: Prognostication for illness
msItem.incipit: 210 And here es a gude rewle þat es vniuersaly to hede of the whylk es gude to be had in mynd
msItem.explicit: 210 bot the influens of heuen in seke es impressed bycaus of debilyte of the flesch and more recepcyon of the influence and in holl men es nat impressed bycaus the mater es oþerwyse dysposyd þan in seke

msItem.title: Tract on multiplication
msItem.incipit: 210 This tabull for mouteplicacion ys full necesare thys ys þo playneste begenyng one twyis ij þat ys to also to tymes to þat ys foure and 3 tymes to þat ys 6 and foure tymes to þat ys 8 and fywe tymes to þat ys 10 and 6 tymes to þat ys 12 and 7 tymes to þat ys 14 and 8 tymes to þat ys 16 and 9 tymes to þat ys 18 and this ys þo conweyng for þo secwnde line fro þo hiest to þo loues and on
msItem.note: Full transcription; the text accompanies a multiplication table.

msItem.title: Table for finding the Golden Letters
msItem.rubric: 213 Nymeri tabulares The dominicall letteris the wekys fro yole to septuagesy the dayes by the same tyme the dayes in þo whylk þat septuagesym schall falle the wekys fro yole to lentoun the dayes by þo same tyme the dayes in the whylk þat lentyn schall falle the dayes in the whylk the rogacions schall falle the dayes in the whylk þat wytsonday the wekys fro wytsonday to mydsomer the dayes by the same tyme the wekys fro witsonday to aduent the dayes in the wylk the aduent schall falle

msItem.title: Tract on finding moveable feasts
msItem.incipit: 214 For to fynd the meueabull festys thys tabull before ys made fyrste ys to be soght the dominicall lettre þat ys had by the goldyn tabull or the tabull made for the dominicall lettre to be funde and þat tabull bygynnys in the fyrst cicull of the son and in the ȝere of cryste 1381 in the whylk ȝere ff schall be the dominicall lettre
msItem.explicit: 214 imbiryng dais fall aluay vppon the weynsday after aske venesday and the wenys day after wytonsday and the wenysday after sant luce day and the wenysday after the holy rode day befor mycaelmas
msItem.note: This text accompanies the table on p. 213.

msItem.title: Tract on finding the zodiacal sign in which the moon is on a given day
msItem.incipit: 218 Whosumeuere wyll fynde in what syne and wat gre of the syne the mone be ilke day he muste know the syne in the whylk the mone schall be ioyned to the son and hte day of the coniunctyon by this kalendere
msItem.explicit: 218 and therfor thou schall receyue the noumbre wryten in the lyne on the ryght syde and that schall thou acount for the of [sic] the mone
msItem.note: The text accompanies a table on p. 219.

msItem.title: Tract on finding the zodiacal sign in which the moon is on a given day
msItem.incipit: 218 If any man will know in what syne and what gre of syne the mone be in ilk day lat hym seke the age of the mone afterward in what syne the son was the day of coniuncion and in what gre of þat syne afterward lat hym seke the age of the mone on the left partes of the tabull
msItem.explicit: 218-219 in the fote of þis tabull ys schewed the partes of monnys body and what parte þerof euery syne receyes it ys to haue in mynde þat the mone abydes in ilk syne 52 howres
msItem.note: The text accompanies a table of days of the moon and zodiacal signs with the heading 'This tabull ys for to know in what syne and what degre of the syne of the mone is in euery day' on p. 219.

collation.note: This collation deviates from that provided by James (1908): It identifies quire 13 as a sexternion instead of a septernion with only one instead of two leaves missing, namely the 4th leaf, and with an inserted leaf at the end. Although there is a parchment stub at the beginning of the first quire, suggesting that the inserted leaf at the end originally was part of a bifolium, the quire numbers, which start with '1' on p. 243, indicate that there is no leaf missing at the beginning and that the quire's final leaf, paginated as pp. 267-268, was added. In quire 17, this collation identifies the 7th and 10th leaves as missing while James identifies the 7th and 9th leaves as missing; and in quire 19 it identifies leaves 10-11 as missing while James identifies leaves 10-12 as missing: based on leaf numbers, this record's collation considers the leaf that is paginated as pp. 397-398 to be part of quire 19 whereas James considers it part of quire 20..
